title="Alex Nelson">Alex Nelson</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>To prove properties about the determinant, it's helpful to introduce the <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Levi-Civita symbol</html:dfn> which is a family of symbols usually denoted <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\varepsilon _{i_{1},…,i_{n}}]]></fr:tex> for some <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><fr:p>This is defined to be such that:</fr:p><fr:ol><fr:li><fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\varepsilon _{1,2,3,…,n-1,n}=+1]]></fr:tex>, and</fr:li>
<fr:li>swapping two adjacent indices costs us a sign, in the sense that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\varepsilon _{i_{1},…,i_{j},i_{j+1},…,i_{n}}=-\varepsilon _{i_{1},…,i_{j+1},i_{j},…,i_{n}}]]></fr:tex></fr:li></fr:ol><fr:p>As a consequence of that second property, any repeated indices give us a zero (e.g., <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\varepsilon _{i,j,j}=0]]></fr:tex>).</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
